'''
This class takes the data location and gives the data for the analysis
'''

class LoadTransform(object):
    
    def __init__(self, df_loc):
        self.df_loc = df_loc

        self.data_dict = [json.loads(line) for line in open(df_loc, 'r')]
        self.len_data_dict = len(self.data_dict)

        self.df = pd.DataFrame()
        self.analysis = pd.DataFrame() #dataframe for analysis
        self.temp = pd.DataFrame() # temporary dataframe which stores customer, orders, payments & transactions data one by one 
        
        self.length = len(self.temp) # data length of the temporary data

        self.cust_identifier = None #Primary key for customer, stores either customerPhone or customerDevice
                
    # flattens the data to the most granular level giving lists/sublists/dictionaries/subdictionaries as columns    
    def flatten_data(self):
        return pd.DataFrame([flatten(x) for x in self.data_dict])

    # normalizes the data by 1 level
    # takes in a dictionary
    # returns a pandas dataframe 
    def normalize_data(self):
        self.df = json_normalize(self.data_dict)

    # cleans customer data
    # customer data needs separate method, as this data needs only one level flattening, unline other methods
    def get_cust_data(self):
        self.df['numOrders']=self.df['orders'].str.len()
        self.df['numPaymentMethods']=self.df['paymentMethods'].str.len()
        self.df['numTransactions']=self.df['transactions'].str.len()

        self.temp = self.df[['fraudulent', 'customer.customerEmail', 'customer.customerPhone', 'customer.customerDevice', 'customer.customerIPAddress', 
                      'customer.customerBillingAddress', 'numOrders', 'numPaymentMethods', 'numTransactions']]
        self.analysis = self.temp

    # to get the column at which the customer data is unique
    def unique_cust_identifier(self):
        for col in self.temp.columns:
            if (self.temp[col]).nunique()==self.len_data_dict:
                self.cust_identifier = col
        
    # flattens data which has more than two levels
    def get_other_data(self, col_str):

        drop_cols = ['paymentMethods', 'transactions', 'orders', 'customer.customerBillingAddress', 'customer.customerEmail', 
             'customer.customerIPAddress', 'numOrders', 'numPaymentMethods', 'numTransactions']

        df_null = self.df[self.df[col_str].str.len() <1]
        self.temp = json_normalize(self.df.to_dict('records'), col_str, self.df.columns.to_list(), errors='ignore')#, record_prefix='_')
        self.temp  = self.temp.append(df_null)
        self.temp = self.temp.drop(columns=drop_cols)
        return self.temp#.drop(columns=drop_cols)

    # Convert the variables to str dtype. 
    # By converting to str dtype, I am converting NaNs into "nan" as string, 
    # when concatenated with other columns, the concatenated result acts as primary key.
    def convert_to_str(self):
        for c in self.temp.columns:
            #if c not in self.object_dtype:
            self.temp[c] = self.temp[c].astype(str)
    
    # provides primary keys stores in the temp data
    def primary_key_provider(self):
        for c in combinations(self.temp.columns,2):
            cl = len(set(self.temp[c[0]]+self.temp[c[1]]))
            if self.length==cl:
                print('Primary keys for this dataset', c, cl)

    def print_dtype_info(self):
        print('PRINT DATA TYPE INFO')
        print(self.temp.info())

    # quality checks the data merged and stores in 'analysis'
    def quality_check_merge(self, col_str):
        cust_identifier_without = self.temp[self.temp[col_str].isna()][self.cust_identifier]
        cust_identifier_with = self.temp[~self.temp[col_str].isna()][self.cust_identifier]
        return (len(set(cust_identifier_without))+len(set(cust_identifier_with)))==self.len_data_dict

    # renames the columns
    def rename_columns(self):
        # to get rid of the prefic underscore
        self.temp.rename(columns=lambda x: x.split('_')[1] if len(x.split('_'))==2 else x, inplace=True)

        # to get rid of the customer prefix
        self.temp.rename(columns=lambda x: x.split('.')[1] if len(x.split('.'))==2 else x, inplace=True)

    # This merges the datasets
    # the merged data is automatically saved in self.analysis
    def get_analysis_data(self, col_str=None):
        col_lst = ['customerDevice', 'fraudulent', 'customerPhone']
        if not col_str is None:
            col_lst.append(col_str)
        if not self.analysis.empty and not self.temp.equals(self.analysis):
            self.analysis = pd.merge(self.analysis, self.temp, on=col_str)

    def print_data(self):
        print('Shape of the dataset: ', self.temp.shape)
        #print('Columns in dataset', temp.columns)
        print('Num of uniques in dataset at column levels: ', self.temp.nunique())
        #print('Num of unique customer devices in the dataset is equal to json file: ', self.temp[self.cust_identifier]==self.len_data_dict)

    def print_analysis_data(self):
        self.temp = self.analysis
        self.print_data()
        
    # drops the columns, 
    # takes lst of columns as inputs and 
    # returns data after droping the input columns strings
    def drop_col(self, col_lst):
        self.temp = self.temp.drop(columns=col_lst)

    # custom add columns
    def add_cols(self):
        self.analysis['billing_add_code'] = self.analysis['customerBillingAddress'].str.split(' ').apply(lambda x: x[-1:][0])
        self.analysis['billing_add_state'] = self.analysis['customerBillingAddress'].str.split(' ').apply(lambda x: x[-2:-1][0])
        self.analysis['shipping_add_code'] = self.analysis['orderShippingAddress'].str.split(' ').apply(lambda x: x[-1:][0])
        def state_key(x):
            try:
                if len(str(x))>2:
                    return x[-2:-1][0]
                else:
                    return x
            except IndexError:
                return x[0]
        self.analysis['shipping_add_state'] = self.analysis['orderShippingAddress'].str.split(' ').apply(lambda x: state_key(x))

        new = self.analysis['customerEmail'].str.split('@')[1]
        self.analysis['emailDomain'] = new[1]

    # Main method to transform the data  #todo: write main method
    def transform_data(self, col_str=None):
        self.convert_to_str()
        self.primary_key_provider()
        self.rename_columns()
        self.get_analysis_data()
        if col_str is not None:
            self.quality_check_merge(col_str)
        self.print_data()
        self.print_dtype_info()
        print('~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~')

    def drop_duplicate_col(self, col1, col2):
        if not (np.where(self.analysis[col1]!=self.analysis[col2])[0]):
            self.analysis.drop(columns=[col1])
        
    def drop_duplicate_rows(self):
        self.analysis = self.analysis.drop_duplicates()

df_loc='F:/ravelin/customers.json'
lt = LoadTransform(df_loc=df_loc) # creates instance of the class

lt.normalize_data() # normalize the dictionary data to one level, thus, customer column is normalized

num of data points in the json file:  168

For further understanding this data, I divide the json data into four datasets as follows and merge them using the methods in LoadTransform class:

  • customer
  • customer_orders
  • customer_payments
  • customer_transactions

The IDs in these columns are convered to string using the method convert_to_str,
and then the primary keys of each datasets are stored which are used for merging the datasets
For customer data, I found primary key for customer is either customerPhone or customerDevice.
The resuls of finding primary keys imply that transaction and customer data are joined on the variable orderID and customer data primary key which is stored in variable cust_identifier; and transaction and payments data joined on the variable paymentMethodId and cust_identifier
The columns are renamed for easy access and clearer understanding
I then get the merged_data using get_analysis_data method
A quick quality check is done on data authenticity, to avoid losing data, using quality_check_merge method
All this is done using transform_data method

class DataAnalysis(object):

    def __init__(self, df):
        self.analysis = df
        
        self.categoricalCols = ['paymentMethodProvider', 'paymentMethodType', 'billing_add_state', 'paymentMethodRegistrationFailure', 
                                'transactionFailed', 'billing_add_code', 'orderState', 'paymentMethodIssuer', 'shipping_add_code', 
                                'shipping_add_state'] # a list of columns to be considered categorical
        self.numericCols = ['numPaymentMethods', 'numTransactions','numOrders', 'orderAmount']
        self.target_col = ['fraudulent']
        self.model_columns = self.numericCols+self.categoricalCols
        
        self.model = self.analysis[self.categoricalCols+self.numericCols+self.target_col]
        self.length = len(self.model)
        #self.Y = self.model[self.target_col]
        #self.X = self.model[self.model_columns]
        
        self.transactionIDSet = [] # transactionIDs which are repeatingm should be easily assessible
        self.threshold=3
        
    # drops duplicates
    def get_relevant_data(self):
        self.model = self.model.drop_duplicates()
    
    # analyses missing data, after dropping duplicates
    def analyse_missing_data(self, c1, c2, c3):
        self.temp = self.analysis[list(self.model)+[c1]]
        self.temp = pd.DataFrame(self.temp.groupby(list(self.model))[c1].apply(set))
        self.temp = self.temp[self.temp[c1].apply(lambda x: len(x)>1)] # transactionIDs that are not in model dataset

        same_order_same_payment_loc = -1 # row loc with same orderID and same paymentMethodID
        same_order_diff_payment_loc = -1 # row loc with same orderID and different paymentMethodID
        diff_order_same_payment_loc = -1 # row loc with different orderID and same paymentMethodID

        while (same_order_same_payment_loc<0 and same_order_diff_payment_loc<0 and diff_order_same_payment_loc<0):
            for i in range(len(self.temp)):
                self.transactionIDSet.append(self.temp.iloc[i]) #{w3jgb8qt, e6vl0gpx, fo3oz01r, lesb2kxu}
                df_loc = self.analysis[self.analysis.transactionId.isin([j for j in self.transactionIDSet[0][0]])]
                if df_loc[c2].nunique()==df_loc[c3].nunique()==1 and same_order_same_payment_loc<0:
                    same_order_same_payment_loc = i
                elif df_loc[c2].nunique()==1 and df_loc[c3].nunique()!=1 and same_order_diff_payment_loc<0:
                    same_order_diff_payment_loc = i
                elif df_loc[c2].nunique()!=1 and df_loc[c3].nunique()==1 and diff_order_same_payment_loc<0:
                    diff_order_same_payment_loc = i

        del df_loc
        
        return (same_order_same_payment_loc, same_order_diff_payment_loc, diff_order_same_payment_loc)

    #change the datatypes of the columns for analysis
    def change_dtype(self, cat_codes=False):
        if cat_codes:
            for c in self.categoricalCols:
                self.model[c] = self.model[c].astype('category').cat.codes
        else:
            for c in self.categoricalCols:
                self.model[c] = self.model[c].astype('category')

            variable_name = {'True':1 , 'False':0}
            for t in self.target_col:
                self.model[t] = self.model[t].astype('category').map(variable_name)

            for n in self.numericCols:
                self.model[n] = self.model[n].replace('nan', '0.0')
                self.model[n] = pd.to_numeric(self.model[n], errors='coerce') # it replace non numeric to NaNs:
            self.model[self.numericCols].fillna(0)

    # describes the model
    def describe_model(self):
        return self.model.describe(include='all')

    def scalarize_data(self):
        # Using MinMaxScalar, so as to not disturb the shape of the data distribution
        self.model[self.numericCols] = pd.DataFrame(MinMaxScaler().fit_transform(self.model[self.numericCols].values))
            
    # returns a series of col_str having unique set of target col
    def get_unique_col_value_based_on_another_col(self, col_str):
        return self.analysis.groupby(col_str)[self.target_col[0]].unique().apply(set)
    
    # bins the col_str with single alphabet together
    def binning(self, col_str=None):
        self.model[col_str] = self.model[col_str].apply(lambda x: 'single_alpha_unknown' if len(x)==1 else x)
    
    
    
    
    
    
    '''
    From here onwards are the methods to plot various kind of data
    '''
    # defines the figure size of the plot
    def set_plot_figsize(self):
        plt.rcParams["figure.figsize"] = (20,3)
            
    # gives count ratios of a columns and plots them
    def get_column_ratios(self):
        col = self.target_col[0]
        c = self.model.groupby([col])[col].count()

        print(c)
        print(c*100/len(self.model))

        sns.countplot(x=col, data=self.model)
        plt.xticks(rotation=45)

    # boxplot
    def draw_boxplots(self):
        boxplot = self.model.boxplot(column=self.numericCols, by=self.target_col[0], layout=(1, 4))
        
    # distribution plot
    def draw_distplots(self):
        for i, j in enumerate(self.numericCols):
            plt.subplot(2, 2, i+1)
            plt.subplots_adjust(hspace = 1.0)
            #print(self.model[j][self.model[self.target_col[0]]==1].shape)
            sns.distplot(self.model[j][self.model[self.target_col[0]]==1]) 
            sns.distplot(self.model[j][self.model[self.target_col[0]]==0]) 
            plt.xticks(rotation=90)
            plt.title("0: Genuine, 2: Frauds")

    # 3D plot
    def draw_3D(self):
        sns.reset_orig() # prevent seaborn from over-riding mplot3d defaults
        for p in permutations(self.numericCols[:3], 3):
            x, y, z = p

            fig, axs = plt.subplots(2, 3, figsize=(5,5))
            for ax in axs:
                ax = fig.add_subplot(111, projection='3d')

                ax.scatter(self.model[self.model_columns].loc[self.model[self.target_col[0]]==0, x], 
                           self.model[self.model_columns].loc[self.model[self.target_col[0]]==0, y],
                           self.model[self.model_columns].loc[self.model[self.target_col[0]]==0, z], 
                           c = 'g', marker = '.', s = 10, label = 'genuine')
                ax.scatter(self.model[self.model_columns].loc[self.model[self.target_col[0]]==1, x], 
                           self.model[self.model_columns].loc[self.model[self.target_col[0]]==1, y], 
                           self.model[self.model_columns].loc[self.model[self.target_col[0]]==1, z], 
                           c = 'r', marker = '.', s = 10, label = 'fraud')

                ax.set_xlabel(x, size = 10); 
                ax.set_ylabel(y, size = 10); 
                ax.set_zlabel(z, size = 10)
                ax.set_title('numOrders vs numPaymentMethods vs numTransactions', size = 7)

                plt.legend(handles = [noFraudMarker, fraudMarker], bbox_to_anchor = (1.00, 0.5 ), frameon = False, prop={'size': 5})

    # correlation matrix plots at target level
    def draw_corr_matrix(self):
        #X = self.model#.drop(columns='fraudulent')
        Xfraud = self.model.loc[self.model[self.target_col[0]]==1]
        XnonFraud = self.model.loc[self.model[self.target_col[0]]==0]

        correlationNonFraud = XnonFraud.loc[:, self.model.columns].corr()
        mask = np.zeros_like(correlationNonFraud)
        indices = np.triu_indices_from(correlationNonFraud)
        mask[indices] = 1

        grid_kws = {"width_ratios": (.9, .9, .05), "wspace": 0.2}
        f, (ax1, ax2, cbar_ax) = plt.subplots(1, 3, gridspec_kw=grid_kws, figsize = (15, 5))

        cmap = sns.diverging_palette(220, 8, as_cmap=True)
        ax1 =sns.heatmap(correlationNonFraud, ax = ax1, vmin = -1, vmax = 1, cmap = cmap, square = False, linewidths = 0.5, mask = mask, cbar = False)
        ax1.set_xticklabels(ax1.get_xticklabels(), size = 12); 
        ax1.set_yticklabels(ax1.get_yticklabels(), size = 12); 
        ax1.set_title('Genuine customers', size = 12)

        correlationFraud = Xfraud.loc[:, self.model.columns].corr()
        ax2 = sns.heatmap(correlationFraud, vmin = -1, vmax = 1, cmap = cmap, ax = ax2, square = False, linewidths = 0.5, mask = mask,
                          yticklabels = False, cbar_ax = cbar_ax, cbar_kws={'orientation': 'vertical', 'ticks': [-1, -0.5, 0, 0.5, 1]})
        ax2.set_xticklabels(ax2.get_xticklabels(), size = 12); 
        ax2.set_title('Fraudulent customers', size = 12);

        cbar_ax.set_yticklabels(cbar_ax.get_yticklabels(), size = 14)
        
        fig = plt.figure(figsize = (20, 5))
        sns.heatmap(self.model.corr(), annot=True)
    
    # plots word clouds
    def draw_word_cloud(self, col_str):
        stopwords = set(STOPWORDS)

        def show_wordcloud(data, title = None):
            wordcloud = WordCloud(
                background_color='white',
                stopwords=stopwords,
                max_words=200,
                max_font_size=40, 
                scale=3,
                random_state=1
            ).generate(str(data))

            fig = plt.figure(figsize=(5, 5))
            #plt.subplot(1,2)
            plt.axis('off')
            if title: 
                fig.suptitle(title, fontsize=10)
                #fig.subplots(1)
                fig.subplots_adjust(top=2.3)

            plt.imshow(wordcloud)
            plt.show()

        self.model.groupby(self.target_col[0]).apply(lambda x: show_wordcloud(x[col_str].tolist(), title=f"fraudulent {x.name}"))

            for p in ax.patches:

3) Explain what factors you think are significant and insignificant in contributing to fraud¶

This needs feature importance and feature selection on da.model dataset

For modeling the data and getting the correlation matrix, I need to convert the data in categorical columns to category codes format. The data types are changed using change_dtype method from DataAnalysis.

Two plots are drawn:

1) First one, gives the correlation comparison for genuine vs fraud customers. orderAmount has very small to zero correlation thoughout (with all the columns). paymentMethodRegistrationFailure and transactionFailed seems to have better correlation with other variable for genuine customers' data than for fraud customers' data.

In [24]:

2) While looking at the second plot, We see good correlation between numTransactions and numOrders. We can have only one of these two features while fitting out model.
Similarly, there is correlation between shipping_add_code and billing_Add_code. So, we can keep only one of these two features
For the remaining columns, we see that the rows and columns are darker and brighter showing a correlation of less than 0.5. This means that all the variables in our new dataset have a significant effect.

For feature selection, first I use RFE (Recursive Feature Elimination) which selects features by recursively considering smaller and smaller sets of features; followed by using XGBClassifier. I also fit the models using these Classifiers and found that XGBClassifier performs significantly better than Logistic Regression, so I recommend features suggested by XGBClassifier

def feature_selection(X, y, num_features):
    logreg = LogisticRegression()
    rfe = RFE(logreg, num_features) # reduce the num of features to half
    rfe = rfe.fit(X, y.values.ravel())
    print(rfe.support_)
    print(rfe.ranking_)

    # get relevant columns
    def get_rel_col(rfe, rel_col=[]):
        i = 0
        for c in rfe.support_:
            if c:
                rel_col.append(list(X)[i])
            i += 1
        return rel_col

    rel_col = get_rel_col(rfe)
    df_temp = X[rel_col]

    logit_model = sm.Logit(y, df_temp)
    result=logit_model.fit(maxiter=30)
    print('for', num_features, 'num of features, model results are')
    print(result.summary2())
    return rel_col

Looking at the above results, the model with the max log-likelihood is also the one with max pseudo r-squared. It uses all the 14 features for analysis. rel_col_dict gives all the 14 columns for 14 num_features analysis.
RFE suggests that all 14 variables be used for model fitting. However, looking at the p-values only 3 columns make sense. These include:

  • paymentMethodType
  • billing_add_state
  • numTransactions

XGBClassifier Implementation

In [32]:
Y = y.values
weights = (Y == 0).sum() / (1.0 * (Y == 1).sum())
clf = XGBClassifier(max_depth = 3, scale_pos_weight = weights, n_jobs = 4)
probabilities = clf.fit(X_train, y_train).predict_proba(X_test)

fig = plt.figure(figsize = (14, 4))

The results of XGBClassifier implies:

  • paymentMethodType: aligns with RFE results,
  • numTransactions: aligns with RFE results,
  • billing_add_state which was among the three most important features from RFE is not as important. However, going back to the correlation plot of billing_add_state, it showed relatively higher correlation

In [35]:
def ann(input_dim, dropout=0.2):
    model = Sequential([
    Dense(units=50, input_dim=input_dim, activation='relu'),
    Dropout(dropout),
    Dense(units=25, activation='relu'),
    Dropout(dropout),
    Dense(15, activation='relu'),
    Dense(1, activation='sigmoid')])
    return model
clf = ann(input_dim=X_train.shape[1], dropout=0.2)
clf.compile(optimizer='adam', loss='binary_crossentropy')
clf.fit(X_train, y_train, batch_size=50, epochs=5, verbose=1)
y_pred = clf.predict(X_test, verbose=1)
